             <div class="lesson-content-memo"> Mass is energy </div>   
            The equation
            <span class="lesson-content-energy">E</span>  =
            <span class="lesson-content-mass">m</span>
            <span class="lesson-content-speedlight">c</span><sup>2</sup> 
             
            relates these three quantities:
            <ul>
                <li><span class="lesson-content-energy">E = energy (Joules)</span></li>
                <li><span class="lesson-content-mass">m = Mass (kilograms)</span></li>
                <li><span class="lesson-content-speedlight">c = speed of light in vacuum, which is a constant = 3 x 10<sup>8</sup> meters/sec.</span></li>
            </ul>

            In different units, the speed of light is: <span class="lesson-content-speedlight">3 x 10<sup>8</sup> m/s = 300,000,000 m/s = 300,000 km/s</span>. 
            A high velocity bullet leaves the gun at a speed of approximately 1 km/s, 
            therefore light is 300 thousand times faster than a speeding bullet.

            <br/><br/>
            c<sup>2</sup> means c times c, so the speed of light squared,  
            c<sup>2</sup>  = c x c = (3 x 10<sup>8</sup>)  x (3 x 10<sup>8</sup>) = 9 x 10<sup>16</sup>  (m/s)<sup>2</sup>
        </div>

